Joystick Reader

This project reads the X and Y analog values and the switch state of a joystick module using Arduino.  
It prints the readings to the Serial Monitor.

This project helps beginners learn:
- Reading analog inputs from a joystick  
- Reading digital input from the joystick button  
- Using `Serial.print()` to monitor values  



 Arduino Code

```cpp
int Xpin = A0;
int Ypin = A1;
int Spin = 2;
int Xval;
int Yval;
int Sval;
int dt = 200;

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
  pinMode(Xpin, INPUT);
  pinMode(Ypin, INPUT);
  pinMode(Spin, INPUT);
  digitalWrite(Spin, HIGH); // Enable internal pull-up resistor
}

void loop() {
  Xval = analogRead(Xpin);
  Yval = analogRead(Ypin);
  Sval = digitalRead(Spin);
  delay(dt);

  Serial.print("X Value = ");
  Serial.print(Xval);
  Serial.print("  Y Value = ");
  Serial.print(Yval);
  Serial.print("  Switch State is  ");
  Serial.println(Sval);
}
```

---

Circuit Setup

Components needed:
- Arduino Uno (or compatible board)  
- 1 × Joystick module  
- Jumper wires  

Wiring Instructions:
- Joystick X-axis → A0  
- Joystick Y-axis → A1  
- Joystick switch → pin 2  
- Connect VCC → 5V and GND → GND  
How it works:
- The X and Y axes produce analog values from 0 to 1023 depending on the joystick position.  
- The switch reads HIGH (1) or LOW (0) when pressed.  
- Serial Monitor prints X, Y, and switch readings every 200ms.  

